<div id="review_204545897" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/204545897" />
    <a title="Dahlia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5862530-dahlia"><img alt="Dahlia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349118879p2/5862530.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/204545897?book_show_action=true">Feb 17, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dahlia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dahlia" href="/user/show/5862530-dahlia">Dahlia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/22844931-the-man-who-was-thursday">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer204545897" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10534411646759652461">I can&apos;t remember the last novel I&apos;ve read which had such a promising start. I was amazed by this book&apos;s introduction. You want to know how awesome I found it? How about the fact I made notes on almost every single page. The characters, Gabriel Syme and Lucian Gregory, blew me away. Their interaction was so interesting I couldn’t stop re-reading some of the passages. The dialogue was witty and captivating. Imagine a poet/detective and another poet/ bomb-throwing anarchist at a party, talking abou</span>
  <span id="freeText10534411646759652461" style="display:none">I can't remember the last novel I've read which had such a promising start. I was amazed by this book's introduction. You want to know how awesome I found it? How about the fact I made notes on almost every single page. The characters, Gabriel Syme and Lucian Gregory, blew me away. Their interaction was so interesting I couldn’t stop re-reading some of the passages. The dialogue was witty and captivating. Imagine a poet/detective and another poet/ bomb-throwing anarchist at a party, talking about life. It’s everything your poet-loving, geeky heart needs. I couldn’t believe the book was written at the beginning of the 20th century. <br /><br />Now, imagine that poet/anarchist being replaced by our poet/detective in the secret Anarchist Council. He’s undercover! AWESOME! The undercover detective meets the rest of the members. He becomes 'Thursday', one of the seven members of the Central Anarchist Council. Then things turn nasty. He thinks they’re onto him. He suspects everyone and everything. The whole thing turns into a nightmare.<br /><br />Now, this is where things go downhill and become extremely predictable. When the detective discovers the secret of one of the council members, you just can’t stop… frowning. The story is not going… that way? No, it’s too damn obvious. <br /><br />But, oh, it does. I won’t go into details. Don’t want to spoil it. After the detective and some other people ended up in France, I couldn’t help rolling my eyes. The last 100 pages were awful. The characters were not boring and the setting wasn’t awful, but DEAR GOD! IT WAS SO PREDICTABLE! I had to force myself to finish the book and it took me days to read the last three chapters. I was going nuts. Such a shame! The interaction between Gabriel and Lucian were the highlight of the story, but the author got rid of Lucian right away. The meetings of the anarchists could have made the story even better, but the author just decided to roll that old religious wagon down the hill without any control. <br /><br />UGH! Three stars. I can’t give it more. Oh, how I wanted to… I really did.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10534411646759652461" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


